    <subsection xml:id="subsec-fourier_coef">
      <title>Determination of Fourier Coefficients</title>
      <p>
        The Fourier series representation is given by
        <men xml:id="eqn-fourier1">
          	f(x) = \frac{a_{o}}{2} + \sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty}\left[a_{n}\cos nx + b_{n}\sin nx\right]
        </men>
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              To find <m>a_{o}</m>: Integrate equation <xref ref="eqn-fourier1"/> 
              from <m>x=0</m> to <m>2\pi</m>, we get - 
              <me>
                \int\limits_{0}^{2\pi}f(x)\,dx = \frac{a_{o}}{2}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi}\,dx + a_{1}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \cos x\,dx + \cdots + a_{n}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \cos nx\,dx 
              </me>
              <me>
                + \cdots+b_{1}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \sin x\,dx  + \cdots + b_{n}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \sin nx\,dx + \cdots
              </me>
              <me>
                	=\frac{a_{o}}{2}\left[x\right]^{2\pi}_{0}+0+0 +\cdots.+ 0+0+ \cdots =\frac{a_{o}}{2}.2\pi =  a_{o}\pi
              </me>
              <men xml:id="eqn-fourier2">
                \therefore  a_{o} = \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi}f(x)\,dx.
              </men>			
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              To find <m>a_{n}</m>:	Multiply equation, <xref ref="eqn-fourier1"/> by 
              <m>\cos nx</m> and integrate from <m>x=0</m> to <m>2\pi</m>, we get -
              <me>
                \int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} f(x)\cos nx \,dx = \frac{a_{o}}{2}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \cos nx \,dx + \cdots 
              </me>
              <me>
                + a_{n}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \cos^{2} nx \,dx + \cdots + b_{n}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \sin nx .\cos nx \,dx + \cdots
              </me>
              <me>
                =0+\cdots + a_{n}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \cos^{2} nx \,dx + 0+ \cdots = a_{n}\pi
              </me>
              <men xml:id="eqn-fourier3">
                 \therefore \quad a_{n}= \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} f(x)\cos nx \,dx.
              </men>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              To find <m>b_{n}</m>: Multiply equation <xref ref="eqn-fourier1"/> 
              by <m>\sin nx</m> and integrate it from <m>x=0</m> to <m>2\pi</m>, we get - 
              <me>
              \int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} f(x)\sin nx \,dx = \frac{a_{o}}{2}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \sin nx \,dx + \cdots + a_{n}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \cos nx.\sin nx \,dx + \cdots  
              </me>
              <me>
                + b_{n}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \sin^{2} nx \,dx + \cdots =b_{n}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} \sin^{2} nx \,dx  = b_{n}\pi
              </me>
              <men xml:id="eqn-fourier4">
                \therefore \quad b_{n}= \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi} f(x)\sin nx \,dx
              </men>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
    </subsection>

